              <h2>How this debt snowball calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool models your debts month by month. For each month it:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Calculates interest on each debt based on its APR.</li>
                <li>Applies the required minimum payment to every debt.</li>
                <li>
                  Applies your extra payment to the target debt (smallest
                  balance, highest APR, or custom order).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Rolls freed-up payments into the next debt once one is paid
                  off.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Interest calculation</h3>
              <p>We assume interest compounds monthly from the APR:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Monthly rate</strong> = APR / 12</p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Interest</strong> = Previous balance × Monthly rate
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>New balance</strong> = Previous balance + Interest −
                  Principal payment
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Snowball vs avalanche vs custom</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Debt snowball:</strong> Debts are ordered by balance
                  (smallest to largest). This maximizes quick wins and
                  motivation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Debt avalanche:</strong> Debts are ordered by APR
                  (highest to lowest). This usually minimizes total interest
                  paid.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Custom:</strong> You decide the order by dragging
                  rows. The calculator then targets debts in that order.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Tips for using your payoff plan</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Lock in your minimums:</strong> Use the actual
                  minimums from your statements so the schedule matches reality.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Automate payments:</strong> Set up automatic payments
                  for at least the minimums plus your extra snowball amount.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Recalculate after changes:</strong> If you add new
                  debt or change your extra payment, rerun the calculator.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Celebrate milestones:</strong> Each time a debt hits
                  zero, you get a built-in raise. Keep rolling it into the next
                  one.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>What if my minimum payments are very low?</h3>
              <p>
                Very low minimums can stretch your payoff timeline and increase
                interest. Use this calculator to see how adding even $25–$50
                extra per month can dramatically shorten your payoff period.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Can I use this for student loans, credit cards, and personal
                loans together?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Yes. As long as each debt has a balance, APR, and minimum
                payment, you can mix any type of installment or revolving debt.
                Just be sure to keep any special rules (like federal student
                loan protections) in mind when choosing your strategy.
              </p>

              <h3>Does this replace professional financial advice?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This calculator is an educational tool. For personalized
                advice, especially if you are considering bankruptcy, debt
                settlement, or consolidation, speak with a qualified financial
                professional or credit counselor.
              </p>
